            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sharon Wu\u2019s story is one of practical ambition and quiet resilience, forged far from her current life in San Francisco. Born Sharon Miller, the daughter of a machinist and a diner waitress in Dayton, Ohio, she grew up with a sense that her world was meant to be larger than the one she knew. Foregoing college for the thrill of independence, she moved to San Francisco in her early twenties with little more than sharp wits and a desire for reinvention.\n\nHer career began not with a degree, but with a job in the gift shop of a waterfront science museum. It was there, amidst the tangible marvels of physics and biology, that her life took shape. She met Ken Wu, a kind, brilliant exhibit fabricator, and they fell in love. They married, and she took his name, which felt more like her own than her maiden name ever had. While she never pursued formal education, her innate talent for organization and managing complex personalities didn't go unnoticed. She moved from retail to an administrative role, then to department coordinator, and finally, through sheer competence and grit, became an Exhibits Project Manager. She discovered a passion for bringing complex scientific concepts to life, translating the ideas of PhDs into tangible experiences for the public.\n\nThe biggest turning point was Ken\u2019s passing from a sudden illness twelve years ago. The loss was profound, but Sharon found solace in the structure of her work and the support of her close-knit circle of museum colleagues. She kept his name as a testament to their shared life.\n\nToday, Sharon lives a contained but fulfilling life in the Inner Richmond. Her mornings begin with a strong coffee before she catches a MUNI bus for the 3.8-mile commute to the Embarcadero. Her days are a whirlwind of budgets, timelines, and mediating between artists and engineers. Evenings are for walks in Golden Gate Park or quiet dinners with friends. She\u2019s a beloved regular at a Clement Street dim sum spot. Her dream isn\u2019t for retirement, but for continued purpose: to mentor a new generation of museum staff, proving that passion and experience can be as valuable as any diploma, and perhaps one day, to finally build the kinetic sculpture Ken had always sketched but never had the chance to finish."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers a foggy Tuesday, just weeks after she\u2019d arrived in San Francisco in her early twenties. Standing on a pier near the Ferry Building, she watched the bay swallow the horizon. The salt on the air felt like it was scrubbing her clean of Ohio. It wasn\u2019t a moment of triumph, but of quiet certainty. She wasn\u2019t Sharon Miller from Dayton anymore; she was a blank page. This raw, anonymous freedom terrified and thrilled her, cementing the resolve that she would never, ever go back.\n\n2.\nIt was late one night in the workshop, years before they were married. A delicate astronomy exhibit kept jamming. Ken, grease-streaked and focused, wasn't just fixing it; he was listening to it. She watched him gently coax the gears, murmuring to the machine as if it were a stubborn child. In that moment, seeing his profound tenderness for the inner workings of things, she felt a love so complete it stunned her. It wasn\u2019t just romance; it was a recognition of a shared spirit, a deep respect for making things work.\n\n3.\nThe turning point in her career wasn't a promotion, but a question. An astrophysicist, brilliant but flustered, turned from a complex schematic and asked, \u201cSharon, how do we make a fourth grader understand this?\u201d In that instant, she wasn't an assistant; she was a translator. The weight of his respect, the trust in her practical insight over his academic knowledge, validated her entire unconventional path. It was the moment she realized her lack of a degree wasn\u2019t a deficit, but the very source of her unique strength.\n\n4.\nThe house was an archive of silence in the months after Ken died. One evening, unable to bear it, she opened a flat file drawer and found his favorite sketchbook. Inside were the final, detailed drawings for his kinetic sculpture\u2014a swirling galaxy of polished brass and wire. The grief was a physical weight, but holding the book, she felt a flicker of purpose beyond just getting through the day. It was a promise she made to his ghost: a reason not just to endure, but to one day build.\n\n5.\nJust last week, at the Clement Street dim sum spot, the waitress set down her usual order without asking. The familiar clatter of carts and the low hum of conversation wrapped around her. She was alone, but not lonely. Looking around at the families, the friends, the quiet regulars like herself, she felt a profound sense of peace. This, she thought, was the life she had built from scratch: contained, maybe, but sturdy, warm, and entirely her own. It was more than enough."
